          content: "# Introduction to HTML\n\nHTML (HyperText Markup Language) is the foundation of every web page. It provides the structure and content that browsers display to users.\n\n## What is HTML?\n- **HTML** stands for Hyper Text Markup Language\n- **HTML** is the standard markup language for creating Web pages\n- **HTML** describes the structure of a Web page\n- **HTML** consists of a series of elements\n- **HTML** elements tell the browser how to display the content\n- **HTML** is not a programming language, but a markup language\n\n## Key Concepts\n\n### HTML Elements\nAn HTML element is defined by a start tag, some content, and an end tag:\n```html\n<tagname>Content goes here...</tagname>\n```\n\n### HTML Documents\nAll HTML documents must start with a document type declaration: `<!DOCTYPE html>`.\n\nThe HTML document itself begins with `<html>` and ends with `</html>`.\n\nThe visible part of the HTML document is between `<body>` and `</body>`.\n\n### Example Structure\n```html\n<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html lang=\"en\">\n<head>\n    <meta charset=\"UTF-8\">\n    <meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0\">\n    <title>Page Title</title>\n</head>\n<body>\n    <h1>My First Heading</h1>\n    <p>My first paragraph.</p>\n</body>\n</html>\n```\n\n## HTML Elements You'll Use Most\n- **Headings**: `<h1>` to `<h6>` (most important to least important)\n- **Paragraphs**: `<p>`\n- **Links**: `<a>`\n- **Images**: `<img>`\n- **Divisions**: `<div>`\n- **Spans**: `<span>`\n- **Lists**: `<ul>`, `<ol>`, `<li>`\n- **Line breaks**: `<br>`\n- **Horizontal rules**: `<hr>`\n\n## Semantic HTML\nHTML5 introduced semantic elements that tell browsers and developers about the meaning of content:\n- `<header>` - Defines a header for a document or section\n- `<nav>` - Defines navigation links\n- `<section>` - Defines a section in a document\n- `<article>` - Defines an independent self-contained content\n- `<aside>` - Defines content aside from the main content\n- `<footer>` - Defines a footer for a document or section\n- `<details>` - Defines additional details that the user can view or hide\n- `<summary>` - Defines a visible heading for a `<details>` element\n\n## Best Practices\n- Always declare the document type as the first line: `<!DOCTYPE html>`\n- Use meaningful element names and proper structure\n- Include proper meta tags for SEO and responsiveness\n- Use semantic HTML5 elements when appropriate\n- Always close your tags (except for self-closing tags)\n- Validate your HTML code\n- Write comments to explain complex parts of your code",
