          content: "# HTML Elements and Attributes\n\nUnderstanding HTML elements and attributes is fundamental to creating structured and meaningful web pages.\n\n## HTML Elements\n\nAn HTML element is defined by a start tag, some content, and an end tag:\n```html\n<tagname>Content goes here...</tagname>\n```\n\nThe HTML element is everything from the start tag to the end tag:\n```html\n<p>This is a paragraph.</p>\n```\n\n### Nested HTML Elements\nHTML elements can be nested (elements can contain other elements):\n```html\n<body>\n    <div>\n        <p>This is a paragraph inside a div.</p>\n    </div>\n</body>\n```\n\n## HTML Attributes\n\nHTML attributes provide additional information about HTML elements. They are always specified in the start tag and usually come in name/value pairs like: `name=\"value\"`.\n\n### Common Attributes\n\n#### The href Attribute\nThe `<a>` tag defines a hyperlink. The `href` attribute specifies the URL of the page the link goes to:\n```html\n<a href=\"https://www.w3schools.com\">Visit W3Schools</a>\n```\n\n#### The src Attribute\nThe `<img>` tag is used to embed an image. The `src` attribute specifies the path to the image:\n```html\n<img src=\"img_girl.jpg\" alt=\"Girl in a jacket\">\n```\n\n#### The width and height Attributes\nImages in HTML have a set of attributes that specify width and height:\n```html\n<img src=\"img_girl.jpg\" alt=\"Girl in a jacket\" width=\"500\" height=\"600\">\n```\n\n#### The alt Attribute\nThe `alt` attribute specifies an alternative text for an image, if the image cannot be displayed:\n```html\n<img src=\"img_girl.jpg\" alt=\"Girl in a jacket\">\n```\n\n#### The style Attribute\nThe `style` attribute is used to add styles to an element, such as color, font, size, and more:\n```html\n<p style=\"color:red;\">This is a red paragraph.</p>\n```\n\n#### The lang Attribute\nThe `lang` attribute specifies the language of the document's content:\n```html\n<html lang=\"en\">\n```\n\n#### The title Attribute\nThe `title` attribute defines some extra information about an element, which will be displayed as a tooltip when the mouse moves over the element:\n```html\n<p title=\"I'm a tooltip\">This is a paragraph.</p>\n```\n\n## Specific Attributes\n\n### Input Attributes\n```html\n<form action=\"/action_page.php\">\n  <label for=\"fname\">First name:</label><br>\n  <input type=\"text\" id=\"fname\" name=\"fname\" value=\"John\"><br><br>\n  <input type=\"submit\" value=\"Submit\">\n</form>\n```\n\n### Global Attributes\nThese attributes can be used on all HTML elements:\n- `class` - Specifies one or more class names for an element\n- `id` - Specifies a unique id for an element\n- `style` - Specifies an inline CSS style for an element\n- `title` - Specifies extra information about an element\n- `data-*` - Used to store custom data private to the page or application\n- `draggable` - Specifies whether an element is draggable or not\n- `hidden` - Specifies that an element is not yet relevant\n- `tabindex` - Specifies the tabbing order of an element\n\n## Boolean Attributes\nSome attributes don't need a value. They are present or absent:\n```html\n<input type=\"checkbox\" checked disabled>\n<button type=\"submit\" disabled>Submit</button>\n```\n\n## Attribute Best Practices\n- Use **lowercase** attribute names and values\n- Always **quote** attribute values\n- Use **double quotes** for attribute values\n- Don't quote numbers that are meant to be numeric:\n```html\n<img src=\"pic_trulli.jpg\" width=\"500\" height=\"333\">\n```\n- Use meaningful and descriptive attribute values\n- Use `alt` attributes for images for accessibility\n- Use `title` attributes to provide helpful tooltips\n\n## Attribute Case Sensitivity\nHTML is not case-sensitive regarding attribute names, but it's best practice to use lowercase:\n```html\n<div class=\"header\"> <!-- Good practice -->\n<div CLASS=\"header\"> <!-- Works but not recommended -->\n```",
