          title: "HTML5 Semantic Elements",
          slug: "semantic-elements",
          order: 4,
          content: "# HTML5 Semantic Elements\n\nSemantic elements are elements with a meaning to both the browser and developer. They clearly describe their meaning to both the browser and the developer.\n\n## What are Semantic Elements?\n\nA semantic element clearly describes its meaning to both the browser and the developer.\n\nExamples of non-semantic elements: `<div>` and `<span>` - Tells nothing about its content.\n\nExamples of semantic elements: `<form>`, `<table>`, and `<article>` - Clearly defines its content.\n\n## HTML5 Semantic Elements\n\n### <header>\nRepresents introductory content, typically a group of introductory or navigational aids.\n\n```html\n<header>\n  <nav>\n    <ul>\n      <li><a href=\"#home\">Home</a></li>\n      <li><a href=\"#about\">About</a></li>\n      <li><a href=\"#contact\">Contact</a></li>\n    </ul>\n  </nav>\n  <h1>My Website</h1>\n</header>\n```\n\n### <nav>\nDefines a set of navigation links.\n\n```html\n<nav>\n  <ul>\n    <li><a href=\"/html/\">HTML</a></li>\n    <li><a href=\"/css/\">CSS</a></li>\n    <li><a href=\"/js/\">JavaScript</a></li>\n  </ul>\n</nav>\n```\n\n### <section>\nDefines a section in a document.\n\n```html\n<section>\n  <h1>WWF</h1>\n  <p>The World Wide Fund for Nature (WWF) is an international organization...</p>\n</section>\n```\n\n### <article>\nSpecifies independent, self-contained content.\n\n```html\n<article>\n  <h1>Google Chrome</h1>\n  <p>Google Chrome is a web browser developed by Google, released in 2008.</p>\n</article>\n\n<article>\n  <h1>Mozilla Firefox</h1>\n  <p>Mozilla Firefox is an open-source web browser developed by Mozilla.</p>\n</article>\n```\n\n### <aside>\nDefines some content aside from the content it is placed in.\n\n```html\n<p>My family and I visited The Epcot center this summer.</p>\n<aside>\n  <h4>Epcot Center</h4>\n  <p>The Epcot Center is a theme park at Disney World Resort...</p>\n</aside>\n```\n\n### <footer>\nDefines a footer for a document or section.\n\n```html\n<footer>\n  <p>Author: Hege Refsnes</p>\n  <p><a href=\"mailto:hege@example.com\">hege@example.com</a></p>\n</footer>\n```\n\n### <details> and <summary>\nThe `<details>` tag specifies additional details that the user can view or hide on demand.\n\nThe `<summary>` tag defines a visible heading for the `<details>` element. The heading can be clicked to view/hide the details.\n\n```html\n<details>\n  <summary>Epcot Center</summary>\n  <p>Epcot is a theme park at Walt Disney World Resort featuring exciting attractions.</p>\n  <p>It is open daily from 9 AM to 9 PM.</p>\n</details>\n```\n\n### <figure> and <figcaption>\nSpecifies self-contained content, like illustrations, diagrams, photos, code listings, etc.\n\n```html\n<figure>\n  <img src=\"pic_trulli.jpg\" alt=\"Trulli in Puglia, Italy\">\n  <figcaption>Fig.1 - Trulli in Puglia, Italy.</figcaption>\n</figure>\n```\n\n### <mark>\nDefines text that should be marked or highlighted.\n\n```html\n<p>Do not forget to buy <mark>milk</mark> today.</p>\n```\n\n### <main>\nSpecifies the main, dominant content of a document.\n\n```html\n<main>\n  <h1>Most Important Content</h1>\n  <p>Some important text...</p>\n</main>\n```\n\n### <time>\nDefines a specific time.\n\n```html\n<p>We open at <time>10:00</time> every morning.</p>\n```\n\n## Benefits of Semantic HTML\n\n1. **SEO Improvement**: Search engines better understand your content\n2. **Accessibility**: Screen readers can navigate more easily\n3. **Maintainability**: Code is easier to read and maintain\n4. **Clear Structure**: Better organization of content\n\n## Before vs Semantic HTML\n\n### Before HTML5:\n```html\n<div id=\"header\">\n  <div id=\"nav\">\n    <ul>\n      <li><a href=\"#\">Home</a></li>\n      <li><a href=\"#\">About</a></li>\n    </ul>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div id=\"content\">\n  <div class=\"blog-post\">\n    <h2>Blog Title</h2>\n    <p>Blog content...</p>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div id=\"footer\">\n  <p>Copyright 2023</p>\n</div>\n```\n\n### With HTML5 Semantic Elements:\n```html\n<header>\n  <nav>\n    <ul>\n      <li><a href=\"#\">Home</a></li>\n      <li><a href=\"#\">About</a></li>\n    </ul>\n  </nav>\n</header>\n\n<main>\n  <article>\n    <h2>Blog Title</h2>\n    <p>Blog content...</p>\n  </article>\n</main>\n\n<footer>\n  <p>Copyright 2023</p>\n</footer>\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n\n1. **Use semantic elements when they make sense** - Don't use `<header>` just for styling\n2. **One `<main>` element per page** - The main content should have only one main element\n3. **Use `<section>` for thematically related content** - Group related content together\n4. **Use `<article>` for independent content** - Content that can stand alone\n5. **Combine semantic and non-semantic elements** - Use `<div>` and `<span>` when semantic elements don't fit\n6. **Consider accessibility** - Think about how screen readers will interpret your structure",
